`fin_range n` is a list of `Fin n` elements, specifically `[0, 1, ..., n-1]`.
`map f (fin_range n)` applies `f` to each element of `fin_range n`, resulting in a list of lists: `[[f 0], [f 1], ..., [f (n-1)]]`.
`RelInt.liftFinf n f` is the concatenation of these lists, `f 0 ++ f 1 ++ ... ++ f (n-1)`.

The membership condition `rule ∈ (RelInt.liftFinf n f)` means that `rule` is an element of the concatenated list. This is equivalent to saying that there exists some index `k` such that `0 ≤ k < n` and `rule ∈ (f k)`.

The hypothesis `h : ∃ (i : Fin n) (j : Fin (f i).length), rule = (f i).get j` directly gives us such an index `i` (which is `k` in the membership condition) and a proof that `rule` is in `f i`.

