This is a conjunction. The second part `(f i)[↑j] ∈ f i` is trivial because `↑j` is the index `j` (coercion from `Fin (f i).length` to `Nat`). The first part `∃ a, a ∈ fin_range n ∧ f a = f i` is the meaningful part. We need to show that there exists some index `a` in `fin_range n` such that `f a = f i`.

Since `i : Fin n`, we know that `i` is already an index in `fin_range n` (because `fin_range n` has length `n`). So we can take `a = i`.

